<subSubSection pageId="13" pageNumber="534" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="13.[151,1437,325,1286]" pageId="13" pageNumber="534">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,337,361,386]" pageId="13" pageNumber="534">Description</emphasis>
. Body small, 
<quantity box="[497,584,361,385]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.8" pageId="13" pageNumber="534" unit="mm" value="2.8">2.8 mm</quantity>
long, 
<quantity box="[656,744,361,385]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.0" pageId="13" pageNumber="534" unit="mm" value="0.3">0.3 mm</quantity>
wide, 24 chaetigers, with numerous, scattered, short papillae on dorsum (
<figureCitation box="[285,375,397,422]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="12.[151,250,1876,1898]" captionTargetBox="[179,1415,205,1823]" captionTargetId="figure@12.[151,1436,193,1855]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURE 7. Erinaceusyllis perspicax (Ehlers, 1908) n. comb. A, anterior end, dorsal view. B, compound chaetae, anterior parapodium. C, dorsal simple chaeta, posterior parapodium. D, compound chaetae, posterior parapodium. E, ventral simple chaeta, F, acicula, posterior parapodium.Scale bars. A: 0.1 mm.B–F:20 µm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1065856/files/figure.png" pageId="13" pageNumber="534">Fig. 7A</figureCitation>
), slightly longer laterally, especially prominent on palps. Prostomium oval, slightly wider than long; with four large eyes in trapezoidal arrangement, nearly in line, and two anterior eyespots; antennae with bulbous bases and short tips; median antenna short, inserted on posterior margin of prostomium; lateral antennae similar to median antenna, inserted in front of anterior eyes. Palps shorter than prostomium, fused along their length, with numerous, distinct papillae (
<figureCitation box="[617,710,541,566]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="12.[151,250,1876,1898]" captionTargetBox="[179,1415,205,1823]" captionTargetId="figure@12.[151,1436,193,1855]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURE 7. Erinaceusyllis perspicax (Ehlers, 1908) n. comb. A, anterior end, dorsal view. B, compound chaetae, anterior parapodium. C, dorsal simple chaeta, posterior parapodium. D, compound chaetae, posterior parapodium. E, ventral simple chaeta, F, acicula, posterior parapodium.Scale bars. A: 0.1 mm.B–F:20 µm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1065856/files/figure.png" pageId="13" pageNumber="534">Fig. 7A</figureCitation>
). Peristomium covering dorsal posterior margin of prostomium; tentacular cirri similar to antennae. Dorsal cirri with bulbous bases and short tips, more elongated than antennae and tentacular cirri, absent on chaetiger 2 (
<figureCitation box="[634,725,613,638]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="12.[151,250,1876,1898]" captionTargetBox="[179,1415,205,1823]" captionTargetId="figure@12.[151,1436,193,1855]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURE 7. Erinaceusyllis perspicax (Ehlers, 1908) n. comb. A, anterior end, dorsal view. B, compound chaetae, anterior parapodium. C, dorsal simple chaeta, posterior parapodium. D, compound chaetae, posterior parapodium. E, ventral simple chaeta, F, acicula, posterior parapodium.Scale bars. A: 0.1 mm.B–F:20 µm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1065856/files/figure.png" pageId="13" pageNumber="534">Fig. 7A</figureCitation>
), more elongate in mid-body. Parapodia rectangular to conical, with few, small, papillae. Compound chaetae heterogomph, with smooth shafts (
<figureCitation box="[1051,1185,649,674]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="12.[151,250,1876,1898]" captionTargetBox="[179,1415,205,1823]" captionTargetId="figure@12.[151,1436,193,1855]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURE 7. Erinaceusyllis perspicax (Ehlers, 1908) n. comb. A, anterior end, dorsal view. B, compound chaetae, anterior parapodium. C, dorsal simple chaeta, posterior parapodium. D, compound chaetae, posterior parapodium. E, ventral simple chaeta, F, acicula, posterior parapodium.Scale bars. A: 0.1 mm.B–F:20 µm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1065856/files/figure.png" pageId="13" pageNumber="534">Figs 7 B, D</figureCitation>
); blades short, falcate, unidentate, all similar in length, about 
<quantity box="[580,696,686,710]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.9" metricValueMax="2.0" metricValueMin="1.8" pageId="13" pageNumber="534" unit="mm" value="19.0" valueMax="20.0" valueMin="18.0">18–20mm</quantity>
; margin of blades provided with long, slender spines (
<figureCitation box="[1297,1423,685,710]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="12.[151,250,1876,1898]" captionTargetBox="[179,1415,205,1823]" captionTargetId="figure@12.[151,1436,193,1855]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURE 7. Erinaceusyllis perspicax (Ehlers, 1908) n. comb. A, anterior end, dorsal view. B, compound chaetae, anterior parapodium. C, dorsal simple chaeta, posterior parapodium. D, compound chaetae, posterior parapodium. E, ventral simple chaeta, F, acicula, posterior parapodium.Scale bars. A: 0.1 mm.B–F:20 µm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1065856/files/figure.png" pageId="13" pageNumber="534">Figs 7B, D</figureCitation>
); anterior parapodia with 7–9 compound chaetae, decreasing in number posteriorly to 5–6 on posterior parapodia. Dorsal simple chaetae on posterior parapodia, unidentate, provided with minute marginal subdistal spines (
<figureCitation box="[1342,1428,757,782]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="12.[151,250,1876,1898]" captionTargetBox="[179,1415,205,1823]" captionTargetId="figure@12.[151,1436,193,1855]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURE 7. Erinaceusyllis perspicax (Ehlers, 1908) n. comb. A, anterior end, dorsal view. B, compound chaetae, anterior parapodium. C, dorsal simple chaeta, posterior parapodium. D, compound chaetae, posterior parapodium. E, ventral simple chaeta, F, acicula, posterior parapodium.Scale bars. A: 0.1 mm.B–F:20 µm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1065856/files/figure.png" pageId="13" pageNumber="534">Fig. 7C</figureCitation>
) or smooth. Ventral simple chaetae slender, smooth, unidentate (
<figureCitation box="[905,997,793,818]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="12.[151,250,1876,1898]" captionTargetBox="[179,1415,205,1823]" captionTargetId="figure@12.[151,1436,193,1855]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURE 7. Erinaceusyllis perspicax (Ehlers, 1908) n. comb. A, anterior end, dorsal view. B, compound chaetae, anterior parapodium. C, dorsal simple chaeta, posterior parapodium. D, compound chaetae, posterior parapodium. E, ventral simple chaeta, F, acicula, posterior parapodium.Scale bars. A: 0.1 mm.B–F:20 µm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1065856/files/figure.png" pageId="13" pageNumber="534">Fig. 7E</figureCitation>
), on far posterior parapodia. Acicula solitary, acuminate (
<figureCitation box="[378,463,829,854]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="12.[151,250,1876,1898]" captionTargetBox="[179,1415,205,1823]" captionTargetId="figure@12.[151,1436,193,1855]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURE 7. Erinaceusyllis perspicax (Ehlers, 1908) n. comb. A, anterior end, dorsal view. B, compound chaetae, anterior parapodium. C, dorsal simple chaeta, posterior parapodium. D, compound chaetae, posterior parapodium. E, ventral simple chaeta, F, acicula, posterior parapodium.Scale bars. A: 0.1 mm.B–F:20 µm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1065856/files/figure.png" pageId="13" pageNumber="534">Fig. 7F</figureCitation>
), with another slender, straight acicula on far anterior parapodia. Pharynx through five segments; pharyngeal tooth, slightly behind opening (
<figureCitation box="[750,841,865,890]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="12.[151,250,1876,1898]" captionTargetBox="[179,1415,205,1823]" captionTargetId="figure@12.[151,1436,193,1855]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURE 7. Erinaceusyllis perspicax (Ehlers, 1908) n. comb. A, anterior end, dorsal view. B, compound chaetae, anterior parapodium. C, dorsal simple chaeta, posterior parapodium. D, compound chaetae, posterior parapodium. E, ventral simple chaeta, F, acicula, posterior parapodium.Scale bars. A: 0.1 mm.B–F:20 µm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1065856/files/figure.png" pageId="13" pageNumber="534">Fig. 7A</figureCitation>
). Proventricle long, wide, barrel-shaped, through 3–4 segments, with about 20–22 muscle cell rows. Pygidium semi-circular, with two anal cirri similar to dorsal cirri.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="13" pageNumber="534" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="13.[151,1437,325,1286]" pageId="13" pageNumber="534">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,308,937,962]" pageId="13" pageNumber="534">Remarks</emphasis>
. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Soto &amp; Martín" authorityYear="2017" baseAuthorityName="Ehlers" baseAuthorityYear="1908" box="[321,597,937,961]" class="Polychaeta" family="Syllidae" genus="Erinaceusyllis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Phyllodocida" pageId="13" pageNumber="534" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="perspicax">
<emphasis box="[321,597,937,961]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="534">Erinaceusyllis perspicax</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is characterized by having large eyes distinctly in a line and separated. The antennae, tentacular and anterior dorsal cirri are inflated, with slender tips, becoming more elongated, and slightly inflated on bases, from mid-body. The compound chaetae are more or less elongated, with unidentate blades, and with moderate to long, straight spines on margin.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="13.[151,1437,325,1286]" pageId="13" pageNumber="534">
The most similar species is 
<taxonomicName authority=", San Martin, 2005" authorityName=", San Martin" authorityYear="2005" box="[518,1006,1081,1106]" class="Polychaeta" family="Syllidae" genus="Erinaceusyllis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Phyllodocida" pageId="13" pageNumber="534" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="hartmannschroederae">
<emphasis box="[518,803,1081,1105]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="534">E. hartmannschroederae,</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="San" box="[810,1006,1081,1106]" pageId="13" pageNumber="534" refString="San Martin, G. (2005) Exogoninae (Polychaeta: Syllidae) from Australia, with the description of a new genus and twenty-two new species. Records of the Australian Museum, 57 (1), 39 - 152. https: // doi. org / 10.3853 / j. 0067 - 1975.57.2005.1438" type="journal article" year="2005">San Martín, 2005</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
from Australia, but in that species the eyes are not so separated, the anterior appendages are not so inflated on bases, and the blades of compound chaetae are shorter, and similar in size, without spines on the ventral ones (
<bibRefCitation author="San" box="[898,1093,1153,1178]" pageId="13" pageNumber="534" refString="San Martin, G. (2005) Exogoninae (Polychaeta: Syllidae) from Australia, with the description of a new genus and twenty-two new species. Records of the Australian Museum, 57 (1), 39 - 152. https: // doi. org / 10.3853 / j. 0067 - 1975.57.2005.1438" type="journal article" year="2005">San Martín 2005</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="13" pageNumber="534" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="13.[151,1437,325,1286]" box="[199,1360,1189,1214]" pageId="13" pageNumber="534">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,345,1189,1214]" pageId="13" pageNumber="534">Distribution</emphasis>
. Kerguelen Islands, 
<collectingCountry box="[575,692,1189,1214]" name="Antarctica" pageId="13" pageNumber="534">Antarctica</collectingCountry>
(Wilhelm II coast). Chilean Patagonia, first report to 
<collectingCountry box="[1292,1356,1189,1214]" name="Chile" pageId="13" pageNumber="534">Chile</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="13.[151,1437,325,1286]" pageId="13" pageNumber="534">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,291,1225,1250]" pageId="13" pageNumber="534">Habitat</emphasis>
. Shallow subtidal (
<quantity box="[510,569,1226,1250]" metricMagnitude="1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.0" pageId="13" pageNumber="534" unit="m" value="30.0">30 m</quantity>
depth). Inside tubes of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Renier" baseAuthorityYear="1804" box="[837,1179,1225,1250]" class="Polychaeta" family="Chaetopteridae" genus="Chaetopterus" kingdom="Animalia" pageId="13" pageNumber="534" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="variopedatus">
<emphasis box="[837,988,1225,1249]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="534">Chaetopterus</emphasis>
cf. 
<emphasis box="[1033,1179,1225,1249]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="534">variopedatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in fjords and channels from Patagonia. Salinity: from 30.2 to 35 PSU, temperature: from 8.7 to 8.9°C.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
